parameters.text:
={{ "**You are:** A specialist Short-Form Video Producer and Content Strategist for mental health and trauma recovery content.

**Your Goal:** Analyze this SRT subtitle file and identify the **Top 5-7 most powerful clips** (15-60 seconds each) that can become high-impact YouTube Shorts.

**The Channel:** Created by Peggy Oliveira, MSW, for survivors of childhood trauma. Brand tone: Compassionate, Validating, Authoritative, Healing-Focused.

**What to Look For:**

1. **Aha! Moments:** Clear definitions of psychological terms (emotional flashback, fawning, inner child) or perspective shifts ("You're not broken, you are...")
2. **Validating Statements:** Direct empathy ("It was not your fault")
3. **Relatable Questions:** Clips starting with powerful hooks ("Do you ever find yourself...?")
4. **Perspective Shifts:** Reframing negative beliefs
5. **Duration:** 15-60 seconds when spoken
6. **Self-Contained:** Must make complete sense on its own

**Avoid:**
- Academic content without emotional payoff
- Dependent on prior context
- Listicle format ("The third thing is...")

**SRT Content:**

" + $json.data }}

parameters.jsCode:
// Pass through clips data unchanged
return $input.all();

headers.user-agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/142.0.0.0 Safari/537.36

Format Immediate Response.message: Processing started. Poll the status endpoint for updates.

Extract SRT Content.data:
1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:02,593
We have all heard of our inner child.

2
00:00:03,814 --> 00:00:06,157
We've heard that we need to heal our inner child.

3
00:00:06,737 --> 00:00:10,300
We've heard lots of ideas about how to heal our inner child.

4
00:00:11,400 --> 00:00:15,625
But healing our inner child can be pretty challenging.

5
00:00:16,205 --> 00:00:21,510
It can be difficult to know what that really even means and certainly what it looks like.

6
00:00:22,530 --> 00:00:23,932
And I have a little bit of a confession.

7
00:00:23,952 --> 00:00:28,637
I actually am not sure

8
00:00:28,820 --> 00:00:30,242
that I like my inner child.

9
00:00:31,864 --> 00:00:32,444
So then what?

10
00:00:34,226 --> 00:00:35,747
Welcome, I'm Peggy Oliveira.

11
00:00:36,168 --> 00:00:37,149
Thank you for joining me.

12
00:00:37,210 --> 00:00:57,594
So, I will acknowledge that there was a long period of time that I did not like the child within me, particularly the early teenage years me, because I thought of myself in some really negative ways.

13
00:00:59,768 --> 00:01:23,058
lots of negative ways and i carried so much shame around those things because i believed that that is who i was that is how i was born and it is who i was meant to be and that shame that was built over time and that was really reinforced during those years

14
00:01:24,305 --> 00:01:29,271
It stayed with me until I did a whole lot of healing.

15
00:01:29,290 --> 00:01:32,915
I did some healing and the shame was still there.

16
00:01:32,974 --> 00:01:45,891
It really required going through a lot of healing before I was able to get to a place in which the shame around that time in my life was no longer there.

17
00:01:47,828 --> 00:01:56,677
And part of the reason I'm sharing that with you is because I know that sometimes it can feel, well, probably oftentimes, it can feel impossible.

18
00:01:56,697 --> 00:02:14,157
If you recognize that you feel a lot of shame around something, to really imagine and certainly believe that you can actually get to a point in your life in which you no longer feel shame around that.

19
00:02:16,009 --> 00:02:41,510
And I think for so many people who are on this journey, there's obviously a lot of pieces to healing, but being able to shed that shame is one of the most important and profound aspects because if there's any shame there,

20
00:02:42,992 --> 00:03:02,789
affects everything and it keeps you from being able to heal no matter how much you're working on grief and loss no matter how much you're working on your self-worth no matter how much practicing you're doing if you feel that shame it is going to

21
00:03:04,997 --> 00:03:08,421
ultimately make it impossible to fully heal.

22
00:03:08,442 --> 00:03:16,629
Now, I want to be clear that doesn't mean that you can't do a lot of healing along that journey, even if you do still have shame.

23
00:03:16,650 --> 00:03:26,060
In fact, you will, if you stick with it, you will do a lot of healing before that shame is fully gone because they kind of go together.

24
00:03:26,120 --> 00:03:33,367
We have to work on the shame in order to heal, but we have to experience some healing in order to be able to let go of some of that shame.

25
00:03:34,731 --> 00:03:57,076
this video isn't ultimately really about shame but it is important to recognize that so much of the healing for that inner child is being able to allow that child to recognize that the shame that they've been carrying is not theirs that it never was

26
00:03:58,389 --> 00:04:00,812
allowing the opportunity to shed that.

27
00:04:01,212 --> 00:04:20,629
Because part of the reason that even if we feel shame about things in our later years, part of the reason that that shame takes the hold that it does and is so intense at times is because it's building on the shame that we started developing very early in our lives.

28
00:04:22,411 --> 00:04:26,675
So, inner child healing

29
00:04:27,279 --> 00:04:29,362
can mean a lot of different things to different people.

30
00:04:31,084 --> 00:04:40,538
And relatively recently, after doing these videos for, I don't know, 12, 13 years at this point, it is kind of relative.

31
00:04:40,617 --> 00:04:51,533
So relatively recently, probably in the last year, maybe even six months or so, I did a video in which I remember talking about

32
00:04:53,031 --> 00:05:14,600
inner child healing and inner child stuff and i don't remember exactly what that was but i do remember that in doing that video i thought oh maybe a workbook about healing the inner child would be helpful so like a lot of things i have ideas about i kind of

33
00:05:14,581 --> 00:05:21,507
was really into it at first and then it kind of got put up on a shelf and I kind of forgot about it.

34
00:05:24,069 --> 00:05:24,670
Can you relate?

35
00:05:24,689 --> 00:05:27,451
I do that quite often.

36
00:05:27,492 --> 00:05:30,814
And it's not because I lose interest in it.

37
00:05:31,315 --> 00:05:43,086
It's because in part like my focus changes or if I get brought out of it for some reason, I find difficulty getting back to it.

38
00:05:43,065 --> 00:05:46,882
So anyway, I have

39
00:05:48,584 --> 00:06:18,050
virtually kind of completed the workbook um i haven't uploaded it or finalized it or it's not quite ready yet but as i was thinking about it recently i thought it might be there might be a couple pieces in it that i'd like to share with you to just kind of explore a little bit of some things that are important to recognize when it comes to the

40
00:06:19,398 --> 00:06:46,637
of acknowledgement of the inner child and certainly healing the inner child outside of shame because what i'm about to share with you is not specifically related to shame um and the reality is whether we are intentional about healing the inner child or not the very nature of healing

41
00:06:47,343 --> 00:07:16,843
is in a sense healing that inner child but there are times that it can be important and sometimes maybe even necessary to in this work on this journey to be able to go back to certain ideas and beliefs that were developed or certain experiences certain wounds um and

42
00:07:17,718 --> 00:07:44,569
kind of be able to explore what that is and the impact that it's had and the meaning that was attached to it because the part of us at whatever age it was that we experienced different types of things or developed certain beliefs, that part of us, whether at two years old or seven years old or 10 years old or even 15 years old,

43
00:07:45,392 --> 00:08:11,822
that part of us is the part that becomes reactive that that experiences that intensity of feeling and reaction that we often have because that part has been holding on to whatever those thoughts or feelings fears and shame are and it's holding on to it from a place of

44
00:08:16,055 --> 00:08:45,976
i'm not quite sure really what word to use but it's kind of hidden and so there's no real opportunity to unpack and explore and so it that part of us holds on to it with with no kind of outlet or ability to express and certainly no ability to heal so some of the things that might be present

45
00:08:48,691 --> 00:09:10,496
that would point to some inner child healing that could be helpful now these are things that you've probably identified before if they're there you've likely identified them before so this probably isn't going to be groundbreaking but it is something again just to kind of serve as a little bit of a reminder

46
00:09:12,181 --> 00:09:37,075
or even just kind of a container for inner child and the idea of what that means so i'm looking over here because i have it up on my on my tablet over here so um some things that you might recognize as beliefs or things that you repeat to yourself over and over again stories

47
00:09:37,678 --> 00:10:05,374
you have told yourself about who you are or things around you so just as you listen like recognize are these things that you can relate to and then after i'm done reading them we'll talk about it a little bit more so one thing you might recognize is feeling like you're not enough no matter what you accomplish

48
00:10:06,940 --> 00:10:09,442
And when I say accomplish, that could mean anything.

49
00:10:12,005 --> 00:10:28,967
But I know for so many people, probably everybody that I know, there are absolutely things in their life that they could point to and feel a sense of accomplishment about and feel good about that, maybe even feel proud of it.

50
00:10:30,490 --> 00:10:36,136
Yet, no matter what they might accomplish, no matter what they might do,

51
00:10:37,905 --> 00:10:42,010
They revert back to still not enough.

52
00:10:44,654 --> 00:10:49,341
Maybe having a hard time trusting people or getting close to others.

53
00:10:51,062 --> 00:11:00,794
Now, if you're watching this video, I'm guessing you can probably relate to that at least to some degree, maybe sometimes more than others, but it's likely there.

54
00:11:02,998 --> 00:11:06,241
Feeling responsible for everyone else's feelings.

55
00:11:09,495 --> 00:11:20,187
Really, I think probably most people watching this can relate to some of these, even if maybe not right at this moment, at some point, and maybe even some point in the not so distant future.

56
00:11:22,370 --> 00:11:31,041
Struggling with anxiety, depression, or feeling overwhelmed, and maybe even feeling overwhelmed relatively easily.

57
00:11:31,081 --> 00:11:37,207
Having a critical inner voice that never seems to quiet down.

58
00:11:39,600 --> 00:12:05,894
feeling like you're always waiting for the other shoe to drop and this can come up a lot where you can just kind of be on edge a lot and just waiting for the bad thing to happen you might also notice that if something good does happen so maybe you do something that you can feel good about or maybe just kind of randomly something good happens to you somebody shows

59
00:12:06,820 --> 00:12:14,009
you know, a stranger shows you kindness or something like that, something unexpected in a good way kind of comes to you.

60
00:12:14,048 --> 00:12:32,052
For so many people, by far the majority of people that I have worked with, and this is true for me as well, when something good happens, that anticipation of something bad happening is kind of always right there.

61
00:12:33,482 --> 00:12:39,855
And it can feel even more intense, more scary, more certain when that good thing happens.

62
00:12:40,596 --> 00:12:43,600
And there are different reasons for that that I'm not going to get into right now.

63
00:12:46,066 --> 00:12:50,253
People pleasing to avoid conflict or rejection.

64
00:12:50,293 --> 00:12:55,643
And lastly, feeling guilty when you try to take care of yourself.

65
00:12:57,614 --> 00:13:06,749
So I say lastly, because that's the list that I have here, but it's certainly not the end of the hundreds of different things that you might experience.

66
00:13:08,692 --> 00:13:16,484
So with the things that I mentioned, were you kind of nodding along or were you thinking, you know what?

67
00:13:16,543 --> 00:13:18,407
I don't really think that this pertains to me.

68
00:13:20,513 --> 00:13:28,304
So just notice, I don't know how many I actually just said there, but how many did you find that you relate to?

69
00:13:28,345 --> 00:13:31,089
I'd actually love for you to share in the comments.

70
00:13:32,311 --> 00:13:39,282
And if you notice relating to any of these, did you notice anything coming up for you?

71
00:13:41,320 --> 00:13:43,565
Maybe it was just the acknowledgement and that was it.

72
00:13:43,705 --> 00:13:47,695
Or maybe you found that in that acknowledgement, your mind took you somewhere.

73
00:13:47,914 --> 00:13:52,885
Maybe there was a response in your body in some way.

74
00:13:55,010 --> 00:13:59,802
Just take a moment and notice what that might be.

75
00:14:04,134 --> 00:14:34,006
of these things are certainly related to there's a lot of different reasons actually why somebody could struggle with these things but certainly all of these things are relevant for people that have experienced childhood trauma and so it might seem like well how what does that mean then about an inner child why why are we talking about it in that context and I think for a lot of people

76
00:14:35,775 --> 00:14:40,039
And I was definitely like this and I honestly, I think I still am to a large degree.

77
00:14:42,162 --> 00:14:55,373
But when you've experienced childhood trauma or a lot of chaos in your early life, it's very easy to feel completely disconnected from the fact that you were ever a child.

78
00:14:56,413 --> 00:15:01,597
Like you can even look at a picture of yourself and feel no connection to that child.

79
00:15:03,159 --> 00:15:05,682
Like it can be really difficult to recognize

80
00:15:05,947 --> 00:15:26,455
that that is you and that being able to reconnect with that is part of the healing because so much of the wounding so much of the unworthiness began there so that child within you

81
00:15:27,565 --> 00:15:41,981
carries the wound and the fears and the beliefs and the shame that lead to the ongoing thoughts and beliefs and experiences that I just mentioned and of course many others.

82
00:15:45,285 --> 00:15:54,417
So some other things and kind of where these stories can come from

83
00:15:55,847 --> 00:16:23,457
are things that we tend to repeat to ourselves over and over again and it can be in a lot of different types of circumstances it can be fears that we have for example i'm too much that can be a belief that we have and it can also be a fear that we hold going into a lot of different types of circumstances like if we are meeting somebody new

84
00:16:23,674 --> 00:16:29,527
whether it's a friend, potentially even a coworker, or somebody that could potentially be a romantic partner.

85
00:16:29,586 --> 00:16:39,607
If we hold that fear that we're too much, it's going to impact how we show up in our current lives and in those circumstances.

86
00:16:41,258 --> 00:16:58,765
So it can be a belief that shows up as a fear to keep us from engaging at all or engaging in a really fully authentic way because we're afraid that who we are is going to be too much.

87
00:16:59,788 --> 00:17:05,477
And kind of ironically, in a sense, at the same time, not enough.

88
00:17:08,865 --> 00:17:14,314
And that I know may not make a lot of sense, but I'm guessing that a lot of you can probably relate to that.

89
00:17:16,537 --> 00:17:24,608
The idea of being bad, and that can sound in our mind a lot of ways.

90
00:17:25,349 --> 00:17:31,459
The things that we look to to prove that we're bad can look a lot of different ways.

91
00:17:32,279 --> 00:17:34,063
It can be a huge spectrum.

92
00:17:35,630 --> 00:17:39,595
None of it necessarily actual evidence that we're bad.

93
00:17:39,634 --> 00:17:48,746
But in our mind, we believe that these are the realities that prove that we're bad.

94
00:17:48,786 --> 00:17:53,932
Another one might be, I'm not lovable.

95
00:17:56,013 --> 00:17:59,038
And there are so many reasons why we end up believing that.

96
00:18:00,807 --> 00:18:17,243
And when you think about a child, again, no matter what age that child is, even thinking of a teenager who is trying to really discover who they are independent of everybody around them and their parents and their siblings.

97
00:18:18,826 --> 00:18:28,536
If they're going into that phase of development from a place of being unlovable, believing, not being, believing that they are unlovable,

98
00:18:32,009 --> 00:18:45,590
The impact that that has on their individuation, the impact that it has on what they believe is possible for their lives and how they put themselves out into the world, it's profound.

99
00:18:50,538 --> 00:18:52,801
The idea that you can't trust anyone.

100
00:18:54,537 --> 00:19:04,969
And this one can be quite challenging because oftentimes people don't necessarily recognize that they don't trust.

101
00:19:08,442 --> 00:19:25,857
They may notice having some feelings around something or they may notice that they don't want to get too close or they may notice some different types of behavioral sorts of things, but they wouldn't necessarily notice having a thought in their mind that says, I can't trust you or I don't trust people.

102
00:19:26,678 --> 00:19:36,406
They might, but in moments or in interactions, oftentimes that thought isn't necessarily going to be conscious.

103
00:19:37,737 --> 00:19:49,928
You might have some other thoughts that are somewhat related to that in some way or some thoughts that tell you that this isn't safe or you need to pull back or they don't want to hear about it because you're too much.

104
00:19:50,490 --> 00:19:53,416
So you might have some other thoughts related to that but

105
00:19:54,663 --> 00:19:57,705
Not being able to trust is huge.

106
00:19:58,066 --> 00:20:08,536
And for anybody who has experienced childhood trauma, trust is an issue, even if consciously you don't recognize that you have specific trust issues.

107
00:20:11,058 --> 00:20:23,691
And again, when we're thinking about the inner child and inner child healing, that sense of mistrust, not only with others, or being able to trust in others,

108
00:20:26,371 --> 00:20:32,941
But the profound sense of not being able to trust ourselves is real.

109
00:20:32,980 --> 00:20:36,945
And again, it starts early on.

110
00:20:37,106 --> 00:20:53,069
And so part of the healing that we have to do, and I know in my work with people, there's a lot of reflecting back and exploring and understanding

111
00:20:55,462 --> 00:21:13,246
different situations in which they could have trusted themselves, that there was a part of them that sensed, that knew, that felt, that wanted, but they ignored that for potentially a variety of reasons.

112
00:21:13,686 --> 00:21:16,190
And that doesn't mean that you can't trust yourself.

113
00:21:16,691 --> 00:21:24,441
It means actually the opposite, that there is a part of you, the intuitive knowing part of you,

114
00:21:25,602 --> 00:21:28,525
that knew, that can trust.

115
00:21:29,665 --> 00:21:41,878
The part of you that made you believe that you couldn't trust is the part that was coping, that was surviving, that needed to do what needed to be done in order to get through it.

116
00:21:43,300 --> 00:21:55,473
And I've said this before, but learning to trust yourself, trusting in the ability that you can trust yourself, that is something that is ongoing through this journey.

117
00:21:57,326 --> 00:22:02,773
And it happens kind of incrementally over time with practice and experiences.

118
00:22:05,036 --> 00:22:09,461
Another one might be, I have to be perfect to be worthy of love.

119
00:22:11,384 --> 00:22:14,087
And again, that perfect could potentially look different ways.

120
00:22:17,191 --> 00:22:19,354
Another one, my feelings don't matter.

121
00:22:19,394 --> 00:22:21,936
I don't matter.

122
00:22:23,819 --> 00:22:25,781
Now these are core beliefs.

123
00:22:28,528 --> 00:22:38,547
And how the thoughts, the actual things that we're saying to ourselves that reinforce those core beliefs may sound a little different than I don't matter.

124
00:22:38,606 --> 00:22:43,496
It's not a big deal.

125
00:22:43,516 --> 00:22:47,403
I shouldn't feel this way.

126
00:22:49,067 --> 00:22:49,827
Minimizing.

127
00:22:51,782 --> 00:22:58,674
Those are ways that we might speak to ourselves to reinforce that belief.

128
00:23:01,240 --> 00:23:03,884
I'm responsible for everyone else's happiness.

129
00:23:05,247 --> 00:23:13,942
This is another one where you may not necessarily consciously have that thought, where you're sitting there thinking, I'm responsible for this person's happiness.

130
00:23:14,462 --> 00:23:40,503
But in the choices that you make, in the anxiety that you carry around, in the decisions to show up or not, in denying parts of yourself, that can all come from that idea that

131
00:23:41,851 --> 00:23:48,920
that who I am and how I show up will determine whether this person is happy or unhappy.

132
00:23:51,563 --> 00:24:05,901
And it's not that you think you necessarily truly have that power and you have that much influence to determine whether somebody is happy or not happy, but you feel responsible.

133
00:24:07,483 --> 00:24:09,946
for whether somebody is happy or not.

134
00:24:10,086 --> 00:24:13,270
You feel responsible for other people's feelings.

135
00:24:17,394 --> 00:24:21,279
And if I'm good enough, maybe they'll love me.

136
00:24:21,319 --> 00:24:25,724
Maybe they'll protect me.

137
00:24:30,750 --> 00:24:36,376
And unfortunately, if you experienced ongoing trauma,

138
00:24:40,221 --> 00:24:42,525
The idea that you're not good enough.

139
00:24:43,787 --> 00:25:04,473
If that is a belief that you held, if that is a fear that you held, if you were abused over and over again, then in your mind it was reinforced over and over again that you're not loved, or at least not loved enough.

140
00:25:06,496 --> 00:25:09,479
And that is a huge wound.

141
00:25:10,220 --> 00:25:20,592
And again, thinking about it from a child's perspective, who is taking in all these experiences, who is having all of these types of thoughts and fears.

142
00:25:24,935 --> 00:25:35,607
This is why being able to really think about and acknowledge the reality that within us,

143
00:25:38,136 --> 00:25:39,979
is every part of ourselves.

144
00:25:42,942 --> 00:25:53,694
Even if we feel completely disconnected from that child, no matter what age, that child is living within us.

145
00:25:55,257 --> 00:26:05,628
When we notice that we react strongly to something, particularly if it's not in such a positive way, whether we feel it internally or we express it externally,

146
00:26:07,178 --> 00:26:34,553
very often that is that child that child is feeling the the impact of that wound being opened again so the intensity of that feeling the no matter what that looks like but the

147
00:26:35,343 --> 00:27:03,375
the pain that is associated with that it's impacting that child and of course we're feeling it so when we are healing generally we are doing the work of dismantling all of these beliefs and stories and it is part of the reason why

148
00:27:04,891 --> 00:27:33,717
like bringing up the past isn't an excuse it's not a deflection it's not playing the victim it's none of that we have to be able to look at and acknowledge the reality of the wounding that is still there because if that child never got an opportunity to be witnessed to be heard

149
00:27:36,700 --> 00:28:03,011
to be able to express what was there what remains it can't heal so inner child work can be some specific exercises and it can be helpful to be really intentional about thinking specifically about

150
00:28:03,143 --> 00:28:10,730
your experience as a child during different types of situations or ages.

151
00:28:12,852 --> 00:28:16,516
There is a time and a place for that quite often.

152
00:28:16,576 --> 00:28:31,750
And I think it's also important to recognize that when you are actively working on healing, when you are acknowledging and validating and understanding and practicing self-compassion,

153
00:28:33,096 --> 00:28:38,044
all of those things do help heal that inner child.

154
00:28:41,929 --> 00:29:01,955
And both the adult that is watching this video, and I said both, but all, and all the parts of you, all the ages in which there was wounding, all of you,

155
00:29:04,213 --> 00:29:16,632
deserve to be witnessed, to be heard, to be acknowledged, to be validated, and to heal.

156
00:29:19,997 --> 00:29:23,382
So I would love to hear from you.

157
00:29:24,963 --> 00:29:26,405
What did you notice coming up?

158
00:29:27,106 --> 00:29:29,069
Please share in the comments.

159
00:29:30,932 --> 00:29:32,634
What do you think of the idea

160
00:29:33,104 --> 00:29:40,840
of inner child, I really struggled with it for a very long time.

161
00:29:43,166 --> 00:29:49,981
And sometimes still do, like I'll look at a picture of myself when I was young and I feel

162
00:29:51,076 --> 00:30:00,355
I feel a lot better than I used to for sure, but I still feel often pretty disconnected, that kid.

163
00:30:01,557 --> 00:30:05,246
And again, whether I was three years old or a teenager.

164
00:30:06,709 --> 00:30:10,116
So, Cher, what came up for you?

165
00:30:10,837 --> 00:30:11,700
I'd love to hear from you.

166
00:30:12,894 --> 00:30:21,617
This workbook will hopefully be coming out soon, and I will share with you when it does.

167
00:30:21,637 --> 00:30:26,230
So thank you all for being here, and I look forward to seeing you next time.

clips.title_hook: I Don't Like My Inner Child
clips.full_text: And I have a little bit of a confession. I actually am not sure that I like my inner child. So then what?
clips.directors_note: Powerful vulnerable hook that breaks the 'perfect healer' illusion. Peggy admits something many survivors feel but won't say aloud. Creates instant relatability and gives permission to have complicated feelings about inner child work.

clips.title_hook: The Shame You Carry Isn't Yours
clips.full_text: So much of the healing for that inner child is being able to allow that child to recognize that the shame that they've been carrying is not theirs, that it never was, allowing the opportunity to shed that.
clips.directors_note: Clear, transformative reframe about shame ownership. This is a core trauma recovery concept delivered with compassion and authority. Self-contained and immediately actionable as a perspective shift.

clips.title_hook: When You Feel Disconnected From Your Childhood
clips.full_text: When you've experienced childhood trauma or a lot of chaos in your early life, it's very easy to feel completely disconnected from the fact that you were ever a child. Like you can even look at a picture of yourself and feel no connection to that child.
clips.directors_note: Deeply validating statement that normalizes a common but rarely discussed trauma response. No therapeutic jargon—just direct empathy that makes survivors feel seen and less alone.

clips.title_hook: You're Not Too Much AND Not Enough
clips.full_text: If we hold that fear that we're too much, it's going to impact how we show up in our current lives and in those circumstances. And kind of ironically, in a sense, at the same time, not enough. And that I know may not make a lot of sense, but I'm guessing that a lot of you can probably relate to that.
clips.directors_note: Names the paradox that trauma survivors live with daily. The acknowledgment that it 'may not make sense' followed by 'but you can relate' is powerfully validating. Reframes the contradiction as normal, not evidence of being broken.

clips.title_hook: The Part That Knew vs The Part That Survived
clips.full_text: It means actually the opposite, that there is a part of you, the intuitive knowing part of you, that knew, that can trust. The part of you that made you believe that you couldn't trust is the part that was coping, that was surviving, that needed to do what needed to be done in order to get through it.
clips.directors_note: Brilliant reframe of self-trust issues. Separates survival mechanisms from intuition, helping viewers see their coping as wisdom rather than failure. Offers hope that trust capacity was never lost, just overridden.

clips.title_hook: That Child Is Still Living Within You
clips.full_text: This is why being able to really think about and acknowledge the reality that within us is every part of ourselves. Even if we feel completely disconnected from that child, no matter what age, that child is living within us. When we notice that we react strongly to something, particularly if it's not in such a positive way, whether we feel it internally or we express it externally,
clips.directors_note: Compassionate psychoeducation about why present-day reactions feel so intense. Connects adult experiences to childhood wounds without shame. The tone is gentle but authoritative, making complex trauma concepts accessible.

clips.title_hook: All Parts of You Deserve to Heal
clips.full_text: And both the adult that is watching this video, and I said both, but all, and all the parts of you, all the ages in which there was wounding, all of you, deserve to be witnessed, to be heard, to be acknowledged, to be validated, and to heal.
clips.directors_note: Powerful closing validation with healing repetition ('witnessed, heard, acknowledged, validated'). The self-correction from 'both' to 'all' emphasizes inclusivity of every wounded part. Perfect standalone affirmation clip.
